{"actor":{"display":"Evin Tunador","id":"evintunador@gmail.com","type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":"1\t# Technical design\n2\t\n3\t**Status:** implemented in v0.1; format may still evolve until v1.\n4\t\n5\t## Scope\n6\t\n7\tConversation Ledger defines a canonical append-only event format plus a local,\n8\tgit-backed storage protocol. It preserves exact visible content while staying\n9\tout of the working tree. Transport is on by default and rides normal git use:\n10\ta pre-push hook pushes the ledger ref alongside `git push` (scan-gated), and\n11\ta fetch refspec stages the remote's ref for lazy merge at read time (see\n12\t\"Transport\"); `cledger sync` remains the explicit path and the fallback when\n13\thooks are declined.\n14\t\n15\t## Canonical objects\n16\t\n17\tAn `EvidenceEvent` is immutable and has:\n18\t\n19\t- `id`: `ev1-` + sha256 of the event's *identity subset* — the durable,\n20\t  source-determined fields (`kind`, `occurred_at`, `actor.type/id`,\n21\t  `producer.source/session_id`, `conversation`, `media_type`, `content`,\n22\t  `links`). Volatile provenance (`recorded_at`, `context`, `raw`,\n23\t  `producer.tool/version`) is excluded, so re-scanning the same source\n24\t  material always yields the same id: capture is idempotent by construction,\n25\t  and the id doubles as the content hash that makes mutation detectable.\n26\t- `schema` version (`conversation-ledger/v1`);\n27\t- `kind`: `conversation_turn`, `decision`, `document`, `annotation`,\n28\t  `redaction`, or `supersession` — an open string; unknown kinds are stored\n29\t  verbatim so downstream tools can extend without a schema release;\n30\t- `occurred_at` (from the source) and `recorded_at` (at append) timestamps;\n31\t- `actor` (human/agent/system + identity) and `producer` (capture tool,\n32\t  source system, native session id) provenance; adapters stamp human turns\n33\t  with the identity a commit made right now would be authored under,\n34\t  resolved by git itself (`git -c user.useConfigOnly=true var\n35\t  GIT_AUTHOR_IDENT`) in git's own precedence: `GIT_AUTHOR_EMAIL` env, then\n36\t  `user.email` config (includeIf and all), then `EMAIL` env — never a\n37\t  hostname/OS-username guess, which churns (DHCP renames) and would churn\n38\t  event ids. Explicit config is the fallback when strict resolution\n39\t  refuses over one missing field (email set, no name anywhere). When git\n40\t  would have to guess the email too, turns stay unattributed;\n41\t  `cledger install` warns. Because `actor.id` is part of the event identity subset, sessions\n42\t  captured before this stamping existed will produce new event ids if fully\n43\t  re-scanned — the per-session cursor normally prevents that, but a forced\n44\t  rescan can duplicate pre-identity turns;\n45\t- `content`, stored inline, with an optional `media_type`\n46\t  (default `application/json`);\n47\t- `context`: repository identity, branch, `HEAD` SHA, cwd, and a\n48\t  dirty-worktree fingerprint (sha256 of `git status --porcelain`);\n49\t- `conversation`: namespaced id (`claude-code:<session>`) plus a stable\n50\t  `seq` (source line index) providing conversation ordering — the manifest is\n51\t  currently implicit in these fields rather than a separate object;\n52\t- optional `links` (`redacts`, `supersedes`, `annotates`, ...).\n53\t\n54\tConversation turns preserve visible roles, text, tool calls, and tool results\n55\tas supplied by their capture adapter. The source-native payload is retained\n56\tunder `raw` as an opaque, versioned attachment for lossless export.\n57\t\n58\tReasoning policy: record model reasoning when the provider exposes it\n59\t(Claude Code's thinking text is kept, minus opaque signatures); never chase\n60\tit when the provider withholds it (Codex's encrypted `reasoning` payloads\n61\tare skipped, not stored, and never reconstructed). The same rule applies\n62\tinside otherwise-visible content: Codex `agent_message` items (inter-agent\n63\tmessages) convert with their visible text blocks kept and their\n64\t`encrypted_content` blocks dropped from both `content` and `raw`, leaving a\n65\tbare type marker so the omission is visible.\n66\t\n67\t## Storage\n68\t\n69\tOne git note per **anchor commit** under `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`.\n70\tThe note body is JSONL: one canonical-JSON (sorted-keys) event per line,\n71\tlexicographically sorted, unique.\n72\t\n73\tWhy this shape:\n74\t\n75\t1. **Branch-tied by construction.** Events anchor to `HEAD` at capture time,\n76\t   so conversations ride the commit DAG: merging a branch makes its commits —\n77\t   and therefore their conversations — reachable from the target branch with\n78\t   no sync machinery. `cledger log` scopes to the current branch via\n79\t   `git rev-list` reachability.\n80\t2. **GC-safe, nothing outside git.** All content lives inline in the note\n81\t   blob, reachable from the ref. No orphan data branches, no pointers to\n82\t   stores outside the repository.\n83\t3. **Conflict-free concurrency.** Deterministic serialization + sorted unique\n84\t   lines mean git's `cat_sort_uniq` notes merge strategy (configured per-ref\n85\t   at first append) unions concurrent appends cleanly — the same mechanism\n86\t   git-bug and git-appraise rely on.\n87\t4. **Clean working tree.** Notes never appear in `git status`; sharing is\n88\t   the fetch → `git notes merge -s cat_sort_uniq` → push of that single\n89\t   ref, run by the default-on transport hooks or explicitly via `cledger\n90\t   sync` (the E scan gates the push either way — see \"Transport\").\n91\t\n92\tEvents captured before the first commit exists (unborn `HEAD`) queue in\n93\t`.git/conversation-ledger/pending.jsonl` and flush into the first real\n94\tanchor. Everything under `.git/conversation-ledger/` (pending queue, adapter\n95\tcursors, lock) is local, rebuildable state — never the record of truth.\n96\t\n97\t### Known limitation: squash merges\n98\t\n99\tA squash merge discards the source branch's commits, so their conversations\n100\tremain in the ledger (notes are enumerable regardless of reachability;\n101\t`cledger log --all` sees them) but drop out of the target branch's\n102\treachability view. A future `re-anchor` operation is the intended fix.\n103\t\n104\t## Transport\n105\t\n106\tDefault-on, wired by the first capture in a repo (`ensureTransport`, run on\n107\tevery append as cheap re-checks so a remote added later still gets covered;\n108\tnever throws — it runs inside capture):\n109\t\n110\t- **Push half.** A `pre-push` hook calls `cledger transport-push <remote>`,\n111\t  which pushes the ledger ref gated by the layer-E scan. Policy: a finding\n112\t  holds back *only the ledger* — secrets never leave the machine, but a\n113\t  false positive never blocks shipping code; `{\"transport\": {\"strict\":\n114\t  true}}` escalates to aborting the entire push. Any other failure warns\n115\t  and lets the push proceed. Installation is chain-safe: append to an\n116\t  existing shell hook, back off with a one-time warning when\n117\t  `core.hooksPath` or a non-shell hook owns the file. The hook script\n118\t  embeds the installing cledger's absolute node+cli.js path (PATH fallback\n119\t  in the script), treats \"cledger gone\" as success, and a\n120\t  `CLEDGER_INTERNAL` env guard (set by `sync` around its own push) stops\n121\t  the ledger push from re-triggering the hook.\n122\t- **Fetch half.** A `+refs/notes/conversation-ledger:refs/notes/\n123\t  cledger-incoming` refspec on `origin` makes plain `git fetch`/`git pull`\n124\t  stage the remote's ref; `absorbIncoming` folds the staging ref into the\n125\t  local ref lazily at read time (every `readEvents`) via the same\n126\t  `cat_sort_uniq` union — absorption can only add events, and the local\n127\t  ref is never force-overwritten. `cledger sync`'s fetch phase uses the\n128\t  identical staging path.\n129\t- **Opt-out.** `{\"transport\": {\"hook\": false, \"fetchRefspec\": false}}`\n130\t  (config), or delete the marked hook block. `cledger sync` stays available\n131\t  regardless.\n132\t\n133\t## Capture adapters\n134\t\n135\t`cledger install` registers per-turn hooks globally: Claude Code\n136\t(`Stop`/`SessionEnd` in `~/.claude/settings.json`) and Codex CLI\n137\t(`[[hooks.Stop]]` in `~/.codex/config.toml`). Hooks receive\n138\t`session_id`/`transcript_path`/`cwd` on stdin, no-op silently outside git\n139\trepositories, never fail the user's session, and re-scan tolerantly —\n140\tidempotent ids make duplicate capture harmless. Per-session cursors under\n141\t`.git/conversation-ledger/cursors/` are a pure optimization.\n142\t\n143\t## Privacy and integrity\n144\t\n145\tVisible tool output can contain secrets. The trust boundary is transport:\n146\tnative transcripts already sit in plaintext on the capturing machine, so\n147\tredaction protects the *shared* record, not the local disk. But once a\n148\tsecret reaches a note, removal is expensive (the notes ref's own history\n149\tretains prior blobs), so prevention layers run at capture and the last\n150\tcheckpoint runs at sync. Content hashes (event ids) make accidental\n151\tmutation detectable.\n152\t\n153\t### Redaction layers\n154\t\n155\tDefense in depth, ordered by where they run and what they may do:\n156\t\n157\t- **A. Capture-time pattern redaction (default on).** A deliberately\n158\t  conservative, versioned ruleset of unambiguous secret formats — prefixed\n159\t  API tokens (`ghp_…`, `sk-ant-…`, `AKIA…`, `xox…-`, `AIza…`, `glpat-…`,\n160\t  `npm_…`, `sk_live_…`), PEM private-key blocks, JWTs — applied to every\n161\t  draft inside `appendEvents`, before ids are computed. Matches in both\n162\t  `content` and `raw.data` are replaced with a deterministic placeholder\n163\t  (see below). No entropy heuristics here: a false positive silently\n164\t  rewrites the record, which violates the preservation commitment, so\n165\t  capture-tier rules must be near-zero-false-positive by construction.\n166\t- **B. External scanners as test oracle only.** gitleaks/trufflehog-class\n167\t  rulesets are used in the test suite to prove the capture tier catches\n168\t  what it claims (secret corpus in, zero findings out) — never vendored\n169\t  into the runtime path.\n170\t- **C. Env-value masking (opt-in, default off).** Scrub exact values of\n171\t  local environment variables / `.env` entries from captured content.\n172\t  Highest recall for unstructured secrets, but `.env` is often plain\n173\t  config, and the transform depends on machine state — so it is\n174\t  nondeterministic across rescans (id churn is the documented cost of\n175\t  opting in).\n176\t- **D. User pattern rules (config).** Extra redaction regexes merged into\n177\t  the capture tier from config. Path-based exclusion (\"never record reads\n178\t  of `secrets/**`\") is planned; it requires correlating `tool_use` inputs\n179\t  with `tool_result` events and is not in v1.\n180\t- **E. Sync-time scan (default on, tiered).** Before push, scan only the\n181\t  events the remote does not yet have. The default profile runs\n182\t  medium/high-precision rules (capture ruleset re-run for events captured\n183\t  under older rules, keyword-anchored assignments, URL credentials); on a\n184\t  hit the push blocks with an interactive finding report — allowlist the\n185\t  false positive (persisted by fingerprint) or `cledger redact` the real\n186\t  secret while purge is still a local operation. Entropy heuristics live\n187\t  behind an opt-in paranoid tier; `--no-scan`/config disables the gate\n188\t  entirely. Scan-tier rules may be noisy precisely because they only warn\n189\t  a human — they never rewrite anything.\n190\t\n191\t### Redaction metadata\n192\t\n193\tA capture-time redaction replaces the matched span with\n194\t`[REDACTED:<rule-id>:<fingerprint>]` — fingerprint is a truncated\n195\t`sha256(secret)`, letting identical secrets correlate across events without\n196\tbeing recoverable (brute-forceable only for low-entropy values, which the\n197\tcapture tier does not target). The event also carries a `redactions` array\n198\t(rule id, ruleset version, fingerprint, location path); it sits outside the\n199\tidentity subset, since the rewritten `content` already determines the id.\n200\tDeterminism rule: capture-tier redaction must be a pure function of source\n201\tcontent + versioned ruleset, or rescans duplicate events. Ruleset upgrades\n202\ttherefore change ids on forced rescan — same accepted caveat as identity\n203\tstamping; cursors prevent it in normal operation.\n204\t\n205\tA human redaction of an *existing* event (the E flow) instead rewrites the\n206\tnote line and appends a companion `redaction` event with `links.redacts`,\n207\tthen squashes the local notes ref so the prior blob is unreachable —\n208\thonest history without secret retention. Post-push purge (force-push +\n209\tcollaborator coordination) is deliberately separate, deferred tooling.\n210\t\n211\t## Versioning against harness format changes\n212\t\n213\tThree layers exist today:\n214\t\n215\t1. `schema` on every event (`conversation-ledger/v1`) versions the ledger's\n216\t   own envelope.\n217\t2. `raw.format` (`claude-code-jsonl/1`, `codex-rollout-jsonl/2`) versions\n218\t   each adapter's interpretation of its native format; it must be bumped\n219\t   whenever the mapping changes, allowing later reprocessing to know which\n220\t   parser produced an event. (codex `/2`: `agent_message` payloads convert,\n221\t   encrypted blocks omitted — `/1` dropped those lines entirely.)\n222\t3. The native payload inside `raw.data` retains the harness's own version\n223\t   markers (Claude Code lines carry `version`; Codex `session_meta` carries\n224\t   `cli_version`), so captured content can always be re-normalized under a\n225\t   newer mapping without recapture.\n226\t\n227\tDrift detection: adapters are tolerant parsers, but each maintains an\n228\texplicit known-skipped list (bookkeeping/UI line types, Codex's opaque\n229\t`reasoning` payloads) alongside its convertible set; parsed lines matching\n230\tneither are counted per type and reported in a capture-time warning\n231\t(`CaptureResult.unrecognized`). What does not exist yet: preserving those\n232\tunrecognized lines raw-only so a later adapter can re-normalize them —\n233\ttoday they are still dropped. See the format-drift roadmap item.\n234\t\n235\t## Open questions\n236\t\n237\t- Path-based capture exclusion (the path half of layer D): requires\n238\t  correlating tool_use file paths with their tool_result events.\n239\t- Post-push purge tooling (force-push the notes ref + collaborator\n240\t  re-fetch coordination).\n241\t- Transport currently wires `origin` only; fork workflows (per-remote\n242\t  staging refs, refspecs on other remotes) are unhandled — the pre-push\n243\t  hook does push to whichever remote is being pushed, but fetch staging is\n244\t  origin-scoped.\n245\t- Sub-turn citation anchors for downstream consumers (intent-recall).\n246\t- Re-anchoring after squash merges and history rewrites — ideally default\n247\t  behavior (squash commit inherits its branch's conversations), which\n248\t  requires detecting remote squashes (e.g. GitHub merges) via patch-id or\n249\t  branch-tip matching after fetch.\n250\t- Whether to preserve non-git-controlled harness artifacts that die with a\n251\t  worktree (agent memory directories, session state) as `document` events.\n252\t- Whether an explicit `Conversation` manifest object earns its keep once\n253\t  multiple producers exist.\n254\t","tool_use_id":"toolu_01UqTnRsR3BAATY92jQzPy1d","type":"tool_result"}],"role":"user"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","dirty_fingerprint":"db9dee3b20ece4c8d09a3feb50ecf84b70c566c31b152350e8bd060a46d4b1d3","head":"82fdd94dda136dcaa0c4d769bbd2f84668eb465e","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-co