e staging ref into the\n125\t  local ref lazily at read time (every `readEvents`) via the same\n126\t  `cat_sort_uniq` union — absorption can only add events, and the local\n127\t  ref is never force-overwritten. `cledger sync`'s fetch phase uses the\n128\t  identical staging path.\n129\t- **Opt-out.** `{\"transport\": {\"hook\": false, \"fetchRefspec\": false}}`\n130\t  (config), or delete the marked hook block. `cledger sync` stays available\n131\t  regardless.\n132\t\n133\t## Capture adapters\n134\t\n135\t`cledger install` registers per-turn hooks globally: Claude Code\n136\t(`Stop`/`SessionEnd` in `~/.claude/settings.json`) and Codex CLI\n137\t(`[[hooks.Stop]]` in `~/.codex/config.toml`). Hooks receive\n138\t`session_id`/`transcript_path`/`cwd` on stdin, no-op silently outside git\n139\trepositories, never fail the user's session, and re-scan tolerantly —\n140\tidempotent ids make duplicate capture harmless. Per-session cursors under\n141\t`.git/conversation-ledger/cursors/` are a pure optimization.\n142\t\n143\t## Privacy and integrity\n144\t\n145\tVisible tool output can contain secrets. The trust boundary is transport:\n146\tnative transcripts already sit in plaintext on the capturing machine, so\n147\tredaction protects the *shared* record, not the local disk. But once a\n148\tsecret reaches a note, removal is expensive (the notes ref's own history\n149\tretains prior blobs), so prevention layers run at capture and the last\n150\tcheckpoint runs at sync. Content hashes (event ids) make accidental\n151\tmutation detectable.\n152\t\n153\t### Redaction layers\n154\t\n155\tDefense in depth, ordered by where they run and what they may do:\n156\t\n157\t- **A. Capture-time pattern redaction (default on).** A deliberately\n158\t  conservative, versioned ruleset of unambiguous secret formats — prefixed\n159\t  API tokens (`ghp_…`, `sk-ant-…`, `AKIA…`, `xox…-`, `AIza…`, `glpat-…`,\n160\t  `npm_…`, `sk_live_…`), PEM private-key blocks, JWTs — applied to every\n161\t  draft inside `appendEvents`, before ids are computed. Matches in both\n162\t  `content` and `raw.data` are replaced with a deterministic placeholder\n163\t  (see below). No entropy heuristics here: a false positive silently\n164\t  rewrites the record, which violates the preservation commitment, so\n165\t  capture-tier rules must be near-zero-false-positive by construction.\n166\t- **B. External scanners as test oracle only.** gitleaks/trufflehog-class\n167\t  rulesets are used in the test suite to prove the capture tier catches\n168\t  what it claims (secret corpus in, zero findings out) — never vendored\n169\t  into the runtime path.\n170\t- **C. Env-value masking (opt-in, default off).** Scrub exact values of\n171\t  local environment variables / `.env` entries from captured content.\n172\t  Highest recall for unstructured secrets, but `.env` is often plain\n173\t  config, and the transform depends on machine state — so it is\n174\t  nondeterministic across rescans (id churn is the documented cost of\n175\t  opting in).\n176\t- **D. User pattern rules (config).** Extra redaction regexes merged into\n177\t  the capture tier from config. Path-based exclusion (\"never record reads\n178\t  of `secrets/**`\") is planned; it requires correlating `tool_use` inputs\n179\t  with `tool_result` events and is not in v1.\n180\t- **E. Sync-time scan (default on, tiered).** Before push, scan only the\n181\t  events the remote does not yet have. The default profile runs\n182\t  medium/high-precision rules (capture ruleset re-run for events captured\n183\t  under older rules, keyword-anchored assignments, URL credentials); on a\n184\t  hit the push blocks with an interactive finding report — allowlist the\n185\t  false positive (persisted by fingerprint) or `cledger redact` the real\n186\t  secret while purge is still a local operation. Entropy heuristics live\n187\t  behind an opt-in paranoid tier; `--no-scan`/config disables the gate\n188\t  entirely. Scan-tier rules may be noisy precisely because they only warn\n189\t  a human — they never rewrite anything.\n190\t\n191\t### Redaction metadata\n192\t\n193\tA capture-time redaction replaces the matched span with\n194\t`[REDACTED:<rule-id>:<fingerprint>]` — fingerprint is a truncated\n195\t`sha256(secret)`, letting identical secrets correlate across events without\n196\tbeing recoverable (brute-forceable only for low-entropy values, which the\n197\tcapture tier does not target). The event also carries a `redactions` array\n198\t(rule id, ruleset version, fingerprint, location path); it sits outside the\n199\tidentity subset, since the rewritten `content` already determines the id.\n200\tDeterminism rule: capture-tier redaction must be a pure function of source\n201\tcontent + versioned ruleset, or rescans duplicate events. Ruleset upgrades\n202\ttherefore change ids on forced rescan — same accepted caveat as identity\n203\tstamping; cursors prevent it in normal operation.\n204\t\n205\tA human redaction of an *existing* event (the E flow) instead rewrites the\n206\tnote line and appends a companion `redaction` event with `links.redacts`,\n207\tthen squashes the local notes ref so the prior blob is unreachable —\n208\thonest history without secret retention. Post-push purge (force-push +\n209\tcollaborator coordination) is deliberately separate, deferred tooling.\n210\t\n211\t## Versioning against harness format changes\n212\t\n213\tThree layers exist today:\n214\t\n215\t1. `schema` on every event (`conversation-ledger/v1`) versions the ledger's\n216\t   own envelope.\n217\t2. `raw.format` (`claude-code-jsonl/1`, `codex-rollout-jsonl/2`) versions\n218\t   each adapter's interpretation of its native format; it must be bumped\n219\t   whenever the mapping changes, allowing later reprocessing to know which\n220\t   parser produced an event. (codex `/2`: `agent_message` payloads convert,\n221\t   encrypted blocks omitted — `/1` dropped those lines entirely.)\n222\t3. The native payload inside `raw.data` retains the harness's own version\n223\t   markers (Claude Code lines carry `version`; Codex `session_meta` carries\n224\t   `cli_version`), so captured content can always be re-normalized under a\n225\t   newer mapping without recapture.\n226\t\n227\tDrift detection: adapters are tolerant parsers, but each maintains an\n228\texplicit known-skipped list (bookkeeping/UI line types, Codex's opaque\n229\t`reasoning` payloads) alongside its convertible set; parsed lines matching\n230\tneither are counted per type and reported in a capture-time warning\n231\t(`CaptureResult.unrecognized`). What does not exist yet: preserving those\n232\tunrecognized lines raw-only so a later adapter can re-normalize them —\n233\ttoday they are still dropped. See the format-drift roadmap item.\n234\t\n235\t## Open questions\n236\t\n237\t- Path-based capture exclusion (the path half of layer D): requires\n238\t  correlating tool_use file paths with their tool_result events.\n239\t- Post-push purge tooling (force-push the notes ref + collaborator\n240\t  re-fetch coordination).\n241\t- Transport currently wires `origin` only; fork workflows (per-remote\n242\t  staging refs, refspecs on other remotes) are unhandled — the pre-push\n243\t  hook does push to whichever remote is being pushed, but fetch staging is\n244\t  origin-scoped.\n245\t- Sub-turn citation anchors for downstream consumers (intent-recall).\n246\t- Re-anchoring after squash merges and history rewrites — ideally default\n247\t  behavior (squash commit inherits its branch's conversations), which\n248\t  requires detecting remote squashes (e.g. GitHub merges) via patch-id or\n249\t  branch-tip matching after fetch.\n250\t- Whether to preserve non-git-controlled harness artifacts that die with a\n251\t  worktree (agent memory directories, session state) as `document` events.\n252\t- Whether an explicit `Conversation` manifest object earns its keep once\n253\t  multiple producers exist.\n254\t","tool_use_id":"toolu_01UqTnRs